import java.util.LinkedHashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class CharacterCount {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String input = "walmart";
        Map<Character, Integer> map = new LinkedHashMap<>();

        for (char ch : input.toCharArray()) {
            map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
        }

        for (Map.Entry<Character, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
            System.out.print(entry.getKey() + "=" + entry.getValue() + " ");
        }
    }
}

toCharArray() â†’ String ko char[] me convert karta hai
map.put(ch, map.getOrDefault(ch, 0) + 1);
map.getOrDefault(ch, 0)
Agar ch pehle se map me hai â†’ uski value return karega
Agar nahi hai â†’ default value 0 return karega
ğŸ§  Example:
First time 'a' â†’ getOrDefault('a',0) = 0
Second time 'a' â†’ getOrDefault('a',0) = 1

  map.put(ch, value)
Character ko map me insert / update karta hai
'a' â†’ 0 + 1 = 1
'a' â†’ 1 + 1 = 2

  for (Map.Entry<Character, Integer> entry : map.entrySet()) {
Map ko iterate karne ke liye
entrySet() â†’ key + value dono ek saath deta hai
System.out.print(entry.getKey() + "=" + entry.getValue() + " ");
getKey() â†’ character
getValue() â†’ count
â€œFirst loop counts characters using getOrDefault, second loop prints them in insertion order using LinkedHashMap.â€

Map.Entry<K, V> ek inner interface hai jo Map ke ek single data pair ko represent karta hai.
Character = Key
Integer   = Value

Entry ke methods
entry.getKey();    // Key deta hai
entry.getValue();  // Value deta hai
Single object me key + value

What is the advantage of using Map.Entry?
Answer:
It allows iterating over key-value pairs efficiently without additional lookups

Can we modify value using Entry?
Yes âœ…
entry.setValue(entry.getValue() + 1);
Key change nahi kar sakte
  
